Mass loss prescriptions deeply impact the outcome of stellar evolution models, including the predicted yields (e.g., Chiosi et al. 1978; Maeder 1992; Stancliffe and Jeffery 2007; Beasor et al. 2021). Stars lose mass at widely varying rates during their lifespan, with a strong dependence of the wind strength on stellar mass, metallicity and molecular opacities (see, e.g., Marigo 2002; Vink and de Koter 2005; Ventura and Marigo 2010). At present, mass loss rates can not be deduced from first principles in 1D stellar models that, hence, rely on empirical relations or theoretical predictions. Only time-averaged rates are implemented, although it is clear that both episodic and eruptive events can occur in real stars. Low- and intermediate-mass stars (objects with initial masses between about 1 and 9 times the mass of our Sun) lose a large fraction of their mass before leaving the AGB. Mass loss rates M˙AGB∼10-8\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
